Digging people out of their (sometimes self-dug) holes and running through decisions for what amounts to half a work day for multiple weeks isn't a substitute for genuine connection, and won't fill gaps you feel about your worth. A healthy non-fam relationship won't ask for that

I share this with fear of sounding like a total asshole, that's how my brain works, but I'm sure someone out there is the troubleshooting friend and is giving up a lot, and attracting some folks who take advantage.

Before this, if we were friends, you could just call me up whenever and troubleshoot your problems for 2–3 hours at a time. I'm sure lots of folks would have gladly reciprocated, but...I knew something was off when my very kind and chill therapist was like uhhh that's a long time

In 2021, I stopped being the troubleshooting/rescuer friend. I'm still the supportive friend, the cheering friend, the silly chat friend, all sorts of friend, and most of my relationships evolved just fine, but I was a little shocked by the ones that fell off.

I have compassion for Asian American men driven to thinking of Asian American women as their own personal pool of Eve’s, but it’s just more fkn danger for women, so sometimes my patience (and courage) wears thin.

As with the ‘Black on Black violence’ bullshit, mainstream narratives tend to accept and even salivate over the idea of minorities destroying themselves, even when it’s actually oppression. Then come the shrugs of ‘lol it’s just the culture [insert diaspora] men are like that’.

If they so choose, men of color are essentially deputized to oppress ‘their’ women, and to stake feelings of self worth on WoC obedience, since it’s a silently accepted way to feel power/control over an out of control system.

Intersections also mean that MoC are systemically primed to oppress WoC in unique ways. While everyone is primed to oppress WoC, including other WoC, MoC toxic masculinity hits different. Retaliation is outsized for womanly ‘betrayal’

It means men of color are affected by toxic masculinity in unique ways. it is weaponized to dehumanize and destroy MoC. Some are portrayed as hyper-masculine, dangerous (Black men). Some are portrayed as emasculated, weak (Asian men).

But that discussion is framed for white men. Intersectional feminism is now somewhat mainstream (enough to be colloquially misunderstood, whole other wormhole). Toxic masculinity has its intersections as well.

We talk about how toxic masculinity is dehumanizing. It discourages the full spectrum/depth of human emotions and relationships. It makes society shittier. It probably shortens lifespans (criers live forever y’all, gotta release those toxins).

The trailer for live action Mulan looks great. But you know, it’s complicated, and I’m over here sighing at yet another erasure of Asian America, which I know is not fair given that the original is an erasure of Chinese culture.

So much of what is widely regarded as ‘Asian American’ culture (read: non-AsA people making stuff with AsA in it) still does this check in with Asia. As if the Asian American diaspora is not American, but Asian. ‘Is it offensive? Is it authentic??’

Anywhoo cartoon Mulan was a Chinese American classic when few are still to be had. It didn’t do well in China bc people didn’t like it for historical, but also cultural reasons. However, it resonated with kids like me, because we aren’t Chinese.

Let’s also Touch on the messed up Mongolian representation. Other Disney movies don’t manage to portray an entire people as savage (no, not even Pocahontas, which I can’t comment on the larger systemic issues, just that both populations were humanized)

That creates complications because it means Disney can not make a truly Chinese American movie. They are so worried about what Chinese people think, and rightly so, because Mulan was a real and beloved Chinese icon.

First off, let’s not ignore that the attempt to get a Chinese American director was completely limp. That gesture already rubs me the wrong way. Second, I loved other Mulan, but it’s also fundamentally messed up the WoC Disney movies were always about real women vs fantasy.

People keep asking me so here it is. I have mixed feelings about the live action Mulan movie. All the following comes as the perspective of one Chinese American lady who wasn’t exposed to much Chinese American culture growing up so ymmv

2: because someone out there probably needs to hear this. I was transcribing because I was considering quitting design, felt like I was lousy at it and didn’t have a future in it. My esteem was so low that ~1/90ing my rate seemed realistic.

1: the worst transcriptions are literal. They include ‘um’ ‘ah’ and false starts where people begin a thought before they find what they really want to say. Truth isn’t literal. As a designer/writer/researcher/transcriber you have to parse what’s there to make meaning.

@typodactyl Ding ding ding. And it is/was often the most highly visible advice. Being able to pretend to not have experience and have that be a pro and not a con is an extremely privileged place (which PoC often learn the hard way.)

Give a side eye to anyone who is giving you advice without learning about your circumstances first. take or leave what’s out there if you sense the advice is not for you, and seek diverse perspectives to understand what you’re going through.

And then I got super angry about it for many years and it was very damaging to the trust I have with myself, and others. I don’t want this to happen to other people, it’s a hard professional recovery. Push yourself but also be v suspicious of cut throat environments.

When I started doing more product work, I believed that I should be treated like an intern, and didn’t think anything of it when people tried to literally demote me or publicly deny my existing experience. It blew my mind when I realized this wasn’t happening to some others.

I wish I’d had someone tell me when I was younger that I knew more than I gave myself credit for. Advice isn’t universal and I was drowning in ‘be humble you know nothing’ when I needed ‘you're learning, but you could also apply valuable knowledge you already know here.’

We even insist on following a single illustration style once one finds a single iota of success among people. I don't really have a proposed fix for this, but it's really annoying me today...so here you have it ⚡️

We want there to be one game plan to 'fixing diversity' in tech, hiring more womxn, helping people get healthcare, dealing with gentrification. We want a rule book and don't always want to admit the complexity and validity of multiple solutions.

It's very obvious in our more obvious systemic problems—monocultures and lack of diversity in communities, sterilization of the human in favor of standardization—but it's also pernicious through even the 'good' stuff.

The thing I hate most about American culture is this obsession with one-size-fit-all solutions to everything. Advice has to work universally regardless of background, processes have to work every time despite context. We're all chasing that singular Thing.
